TY  - JOUR
T1  - Financial Frictions and Fluctuations in Volatility
AU  - Arellano, Cristina
AU  - Bai, Yan
AU  - Kehoe, Patrick J.
Y1  - 2018/11/28
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/701792
DO  - 10.1086/701792
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2049
EP  - 2103
VL  - 127
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The US Great Recession featured a large decline in output and labor, tighter financial conditions, and a large increase in firm growth dispersion. We build a model in which increased volatility at the firm level generates a downturn and worsened credit conditions. The key idea is that hiring inputs is risky because financial frictions limit firms? ability to insure against shocks. An increase in volatility induces firms to reduce their inputs to reduce such risk. Our model can generate most of the decline in output and labor in the Great Recession and the observed increase in firms? interest rate spreads.
AB  - The US Great Recession featured a large decline in output and labor, tighter financial conditions, and a large increase in firm growth dispersion. We build a model in which increased volatility at the firm level generates a downturn and worsened credit conditions. The key idea is that hiring inputs is risky because financial frictions limit firms? ability to insure against shocks. An increase in volatility induces firms to reduce their inputs to reduce such risk. Our model can generate most of the decline in output and labor in the Great Recession and the observed increase in firms? interest rate spreads.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/701792
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/701792
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Shocks versus Responsiveness: What Drives Time-Varying Dispersion?
AU  - Berger, David
AU  - Vavra, Joseph
Y1  - 2018/11/28
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/701790
DO  - 10.1086/701790
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2104
EP  - 2142
VL  - 127
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The dispersion of many economic variables is countercyclical. What drives this fact? Greater dispersion could arise from greater volatility of shocks or from agents responding more to shocks of constant size. Without data separately measuring exogenous shocks and endogenous responses, a theoretical debate between these explanations has emerged. In this paper, we provide novel identification using price data in the open-economy environment: using confidential BLS microdata, we document a robust positive relationship between exchange rate pass-through and the dispersion of item-level price changes. We then show that this relationship supports models with time-varying responsiveness.
AB  - The dispersion of many economic variables is countercyclical. What drives this fact? Greater dispersion could arise from greater volatility of shocks or from agents responding more to shocks of constant size. Without data separately measuring exogenous shocks and endogenous responses, a theoretical debate between these explanations has emerged. In this paper, we provide novel identification using price data in the open-economy environment: using confidential BLS microdata, we document a robust positive relationship between exchange rate pass-through and the dispersion of item-level price changes. We then show that this relationship supports models with time-varying responsiveness.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/701790
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/701790
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Trouble in the Tails? What We Know about Earnings Nonresponse 30 Years after Lillard, Smith, and Welch
AU  - Bollinger, Christopher R.
AU  - Hirsch, Barry T.
AU  - Hokayem, Charles M.
AU  - Ziliak, James P.
Y1  - 2018/12/03
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/701807
DO  - 10.1086/701807
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2143
EP  - 2185
VL  - 127
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Earnings nonresponse in household surveys is widespread, yet there is limited knowledge of how nonresponse biases earnings measures. We examine the consequences of nonresponse on earnings gaps and inequality using Current Population Survey individual records linked to administrative earnings data. The common assumption that earnings are missing at random is rejected. Nonresponse across the earnings distribution is U-shaped, highest in the left and right tails. Inequality measures differ between household and administrative data due in part to nonresponse. Nonresponse biases earnings differentials by race, gender, and education, particularly in the tails. Flexible copula-based models can account for nonrandom nonresponse.
AB  - Earnings nonresponse in household surveys is widespread, yet there is limited knowledge of how nonresponse biases earnings measures. We examine the consequences of nonresponse on earnings gaps and inequality using Current Population Survey individual records linked to administrative earnings data. The common assumption that earnings are missing at random is rejected. Nonresponse across the earnings distribution is U-shaped, highest in the left and right tails. Inequality measures differ between household and administrative data due in part to nonresponse. Nonresponse biases earnings differentials by race, gender, and education, particularly in the tails. Flexible copula-based models can account for nonrandom nonresponse.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/701807
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/701807
Y2  - 2024/03/20
