TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Gender Gap between Earnings Distributions
AU  - Maasoumi, Esfandiar
AU  - Wang, Le
Y1  - 2018/11/28
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/701788
DO  - 10.1086/701788
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2438
EP  - 2504
VL  - 127
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We advocate a different approach to measure the gender gap, summarizing each distribution by suitable evaluative functions and computing the difference between the evaluations. Unlike the conventional approach, ours does not assume rank invariance. We discuss the decision-theoretic framework behind different functions and introduce measures based on entropy functions. We further adopt quantile-copula approaches to account for selection into full-time employment and discuss how to take into account nonmarket values in measuring the gap. The evolution of the gender gap depends on the measure of it and whether nonmarket values are incorporated. We further assess and challenge a variety of assumptions, hypotheses, and findings in the literature.
AB  - We advocate a different approach to measure the gender gap, summarizing each distribution by suitable evaluative functions and computing the difference between the evaluations. Unlike the conventional approach, ours does not assume rank invariance. We discuss the decision-theoretic framework behind different functions and introduce measures based on entropy functions. We further adopt quantile-copula approaches to account for selection into full-time employment and discuss how to take into account nonmarket values in measuring the gap. The evolution of the gender gap depends on the measure of it and whether nonmarket values are incorporated. We further assess and challenge a variety of assumptions, hypotheses, and findings in the literature.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/701788
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/701788
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Employment Hysteresis from the Great Recession
AU  - Yagan, Danny
Y1  - 2018/12/03
PY  - 2018
DA  - 2019/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/701809
DO  - 10.1086/701809
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 2505
EP  - 2558
VL  - 127
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper uses US local areas as a laboratory to test for long-term impacts of the Great Recession. In administrative longitudinal data, I estimate that exposure to a 1 percentage point larger 2007?9 local unemployment shock reduced 2015 working-age employment rates by over 0.3 percentage points. Rescaled, this long-term recession impact accounts for over half of the 2007?15 US age-adjusted employment decline. Impacts were larger among older and lower-earning individuals and typically involved a layoff but are present even in a mass-layoffs sample. Disability insurance and out-migration yielded little income replacement. These findings reveal that the Great Recession imposed employment and income losses even after unemployment rates signaled recovery.
AB  - This paper uses US local areas as a laboratory to test for long-term impacts of the Great Recession. In administrative longitudinal data, I estimate that exposure to a 1 percentage point larger 2007?9 local unemployment shock reduced 2015 working-age employment rates by over 0.3 percentage points. Rescaled, this long-term recession impact accounts for over half of the 2007?15 US age-adjusted employment decline. Impacts were larger among older and lower-earning individuals and typically involved a layoff but are present even in a mass-layoffs sample. Disability insurance and out-migration yielded little income replacement. These findings reveal that the Great Recession imposed employment and income losses even after unemployment rates signaled recovery.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/701809
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/701809
Y2  - 2024/03/20
